DCSightseers.DCDescription: The Official Residence and Workplace of the President of The United States. You may view the white house as you are walking past the outside or if you wish to tour the building, tours are available free of charge, all that is needed is to request a tour and proof of identification

The building that has housed Congress since 1800. The United States Capital has been the place that Congress meets to write and signs laws and where the president does their annual State of the Union speeches. If you wish to tour the United States Capital, it is recommended to make a reservation ahead of time.

This 555 ft monument was built to honor and commemorate the 1st president of the united states and commander in chief of the continental army during the revolutionary war. You are able to tour the inside and take the elevator to the top for a bird’s eye view of DC.

This memorial was built to honor and commemorate the 16th president of the united states, Abraham Lincoln. Feel free to walk around inside the memorial and learn about the history and legacy of Lincoln and what the memorial has meant in the last 100 years.
DCSightseers.DCLocation: 2 Lincoln Memorial Cir NW, Washington, DC 20002

DCSightseers.DCName: Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History
DCSightseers.DCDescription: One of the many Museums administered by the Smithsonian Institution, the world’s largest museum, education, and research institution. Explore the history of our natural world and learn of the billions of years of transformation our world has been through.
DCSightseers.DCLocation: 10th St. & Constitution Ave. NW, Washington, DC 20560

DCSightseers.DCDescription: The official memorial of the Holocaust, providing documentation, study and history of the holocaust. Their mission is to help leaders and the people of the world to confront hatred and prevent genocide.
DCSightseers.DCLocation: 100 Raoul Wallenberg Pl SW, Washington, DC 20024

DCSightseers.DCDescription: One of the oldest botanical gardens in the country, learn about many different plants of other regions and their habitat along with their aesthetic, cultural and ecological importance.

DCSightseers.DCName: Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture
DCSightseers.DCDescription: Learn about the richness, diversity, struggle and the importance of African American history and culture. One of the most visited Smithsonian museums and has earned critical praise, this museum is definitely a place you should visit while in DC.

A research library that serves as the national library of the United States. It has a collection of 173 million items in more than 470 different languages. It also serves as the United States oldest federal cultural institution

This memorial was built to honor the 3rd president of the united states, Founder of the Democratic-Republican Party, and author of the Declaration of Independence, Thomas Jefferson. You'll find quotes from Jefferson for you to read of his ideologies and beliefs.
DCSightseers.DCLocation: 16 E Basin Dr SW, Washington, DC 20242
